Mei's Stage
London —— Facing Britain's new prime minister Theresa May is a daunting task: implementing the electorate's demand to "exit the EU" — or more accurately, the voters of England and Wales — and managing the far-reaching consequences of this undertaking.
The challenge she faces surpasses that of all previous prime ministers in recent years.
But she may have the capability to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, May has all the tools needed to complete the task in her hands.
She is intelligent and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is unbound by any ideology, very adept at taking control, and operates within self-imposed boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues she handles.
May has won the majority of the battles she has been involved in and is ruthless with those who have treated her with underhanded tactics.
But she has made few enemies within her party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — one she needs to fully utilize to lead Britain's exit from the EU.
The process of Britain's exit from the EU has already begun, there is no doubt about it.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated that "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers have all supported her view.
But May has not yet given an exact definition of Britain's exit from the EU.
This task is very difficult to accomplish.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
It is hard to clearly know what you will actually end up eating.
A Northern Ireland "Ulster Fry"—eggs, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes—with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you may feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit in Britain.
Some may focus primarily on preventing EU labor from entering Britain.
Others may be more concerned with securing access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, Britain cannot order every single item on the menu.
The reality often overlooked by the Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win popularity or punish Britain for rejecting the EU (such inflammatory rhetoric sometimes dominates, as when the new British foreign secretary, Boris Johnson, referred to "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we British often forget that everyone — including the EU and all its member states — has political or commercial interests they are committed to protecting.
For May, the core challenge over the next few months will be to determine what Britain's objectives should be, based on reality, after the difficult negotiations on its relationship with the EU (and with the world in the area of trade) begin?
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six separate topics that will need individual negotiations), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
By the time the negotiations are completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may already be starting university!
We must clarify our priorities to prevent the negotiations from dragging on even longer.
The goal is certainly to strike a balance between allowing British goods and services (especially financial services) to enter other European countries and restricting the entry of EU citizens into Britain.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they need to make in others.
May needs to make full use of her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that the discontented are not just a part of the population — a result that is inevitable — but all of them.
This will intensify another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing divide in British society exposed by Brexit.
The blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, having long been alienated from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by globalization's so-called agent—the EU.
England's metropolitan areas — particularly London — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have gained nothing from it.
Due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn, many members of the blue-collar working class ultimately fell prey to the populist promises of the Brexit campaign.
"We will reverse globalization," they said.
"We will get rid of immigrants who are driving down wages and transfer hundreds of millions of pounds originally given to the EU into public services."
They promised that Brexit would allow Britain to return to a safer, more prosperous past.
Leave Brexiters unable to truly deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can immigration from the EU be cut off.
Any such move would only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturns lead to a decrease in immigration, the workers who voted for Brexit may still find low-paying jobs to remain low-paying and public services to remain under heavy pressure, leaving them disheartened.
This is unlikely to lead to an improvement in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has unleashed a populist emotional storm that is difficult to control.
Just as Donald Trump has been unable to improve the situation of working-class American voters, Brexit, no matter how the circumstances may seem, will entirely fail to deliver benefits to those who chose it.
Despite her many strengths, such challenges may still prove insurmountable for May.
